 }

Hi.

In "The Asynchronous Initialization Pattern" you say you can use the pattern like this:

var myInstance = new MyFundamentalType();  
// Danger: the instance is not initialized here!  
await myInstance.Initialization;  
// OK: the instance is initialized now.

But thinking your fundamental type is a view model, you cant call it from the views constructor, since is not async.   
What am I missing?

Thanks for the post. It would work just as well to do this also, correct? From my testing it seems to anyway.

 public MyFundamentalType()  
 {  
 InitializeAsync().GetAwaiter().GetResult();  
 }

Note, in the async method you might need to set ConfigureAwait(false) on the async calls within InitializeAsync. Cheers.

Hi Stephen!  
I am troubled by a seemingly difficult solution and even though it now seems to work I decided to submit it to you in the light of your articles and also the comments you gave below to others.

I have a UWP app and I need to set the ApplicationTheme (Dark or Light). This enum is taken from a string which is in the LocalSettings files of the UWP app. So I need to open a file there, read it and return the content to the app. The point about the ApplicationTheme is that you can only set it when the app launches, otherwise you receive a NotSupported exception according to the docs (and I can confirm!). So this means that I need to open and read the file in the top-level constructor of App.cs of the uwp app. The only solution I found that does not crash is the following and follows your pattern except in the App.cs constructor (hence my concern)

 public App()  
 {  
 InitializeComponent();  
 RequestedTheme = Task.Run(()=>ThemeSelectorService.InitializeAppTheme).GetAwaiter().GetResult();  
 }

And the static ThemeSelectorService follows your pattern somewhat

It has the property  
 public static Task<applicationtheme> InitializeAppTheme { get; set; } = GetAppThemeAsync();

And

 public static async Task<applicationtheme> GetAppThemeAsync()  
 {  
 return await LoadAppThemeFromSettingsAsync();  
 }

The LoadAppThemeFromSettingsAsync() is open and reads the file that contains the theme string.

I could make it work only with Task.Run, the other options crashed the app literally!  
I am concerned about the practice of this method, if you have any better solution for this edge case? Thank you for any guidance
